\par "The polities of the nineteenth and twentieth centuries swung between extremes of nationalism and polyethnic multiculturalism. 
Following the Great War (1914-8), the disintegration of most of the continental empires - notably the Habsburg and Ottoman - led to a resurgence of a particularly virulent strain of the former, dressed as Fascism, Nazism, and Stalinism. 
\par The aftermath of the Second World War brought on a predictable backlash in the West against all manner of nationalism and racism. The {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname country-region}}USSR{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname country-region}}Yugoslavia{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname country-region}}Czech Republic{\*\xmlclose}
