 deregulation, liberalization, tax reform, cutting red tape and tariff reductions. Aided by a free trade agreement with {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname country-region}}America{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 passed by Congress in 2001, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname country-region}}Jordan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}'s exports to the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname country-region}}
United States{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} last year soared from $16 million in 1998 to $400 million in 2002.
\par A similar nostrum is being administered to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname country-region}}Morocco{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, partly to spite the European Union and its glacial "Barcelona Process" Euro-Mediterranean Partnership. But, as everyone realizes, the region's problems run deeper than any tweaking of the customs code.
\par The "Arab Human Development Report 2002", published in June 2002 by the United Nations Development Program (UNDP), was composed entirely by Arab scholars. It charts the predictably dismal landscape: one in five inhabitants survives on less than $2 a day
; annual growth in income per capita over the last 20 years, at 0.5 percent, exceeded only sub-Saharan {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}Africa{\*\xmlclose}'s; one in six is unemployed.
\par The region's three "deficits", laments the report, are freedom, knowledge and manpower. Arab polities and societies a
re autocratic and intolerant. Illiteracy is still rampant and education poor. Women - half the workforce - are ill-treated and excluded. Pervasive Islamization replaced earlier militant ideologies in stifling creativity and growth.
\par In an article titled "Mi
ddle East Economies: A Survey of Current Problems and Issues", published in the September 1999 issue of the Middle East Review of International Affairs, Ali Abootalebi, assistant professor of political science at the University of Wisconsin, Eau Claire, c
oncluded:
\par }{\rtlch \ab\ai\af0\afs24 \ltrch \b\i\f0\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 "The {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}Middle East{\*\xmlclose} is second only to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}Africa{\*\xmlclose}
 as the least developed region in the world. It has already lost much of its strategic importance since the Soviet Union's demise ... Most Middle Eastern states ... probably do, possess the necessary techno
cratic and professional personnel to run state affairs in an efficient and modern manner .... (but not) the willingness or ability of the elites in charge to disengage the old coalitional interests that dominate governments in these countries."}{\rtlch 
\af0\afs24 \ltrch \f0\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033 
\par The war with {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname country-region}}Iraq{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} changed all that. This was the fervent hope of intellectuals throughout the region, even those viscerally opposed to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname country-region}}America{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}'s high-handed hegemony. But this may well be only another false dawn in many. The inevitable massive postwar damage to the a
rea's fragile economies will spawn added oppression rather than enhance democracy.
\par According to The Economist, the military buildup has already injected $2 billion into {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname country-region}}Kuwait{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
's economy, equal to 6 percent of its GDP. Prices of everything - from real estate to cars - are rising fast. The stock exchange index has soared by one third. American largesse extends to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1
{\factoidname country-region}}Turkey{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - the recipient of $5 billion in grants, $1 billion in oil and $10 billion in loan guarantees. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname country-region}}Egypt
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname country-region}}Jordan{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} will reap $1 billion apiece and, possibly, subsidized Saudi oil as well. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1
{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname country-region}}Israel{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} will abscond with $8 billion in collateral and billions in cash.
\par But the party may be short-lived, especially since the war did not prove to be as decisive and nippy as the Americans foresaw.
\par Stratfor, the strategic forecasting consultancy, correctly observes that the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname country-region}}United States{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 is likely to encourage American oil companies to boost {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname country-region}}Iraq{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}'s postbellum production. With {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname country-region}}Venezuela{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} back on line and global tensions eased, deteriorating crude prices may adversely affect oil-dependent countries from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname country-region}}Iran{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname country-region}}Algeria{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}.
\par The resulting social and political unrest - coupled with violent, though typically impotent, protests against the war, America and the political leadership - is unlikely to convince panicky tottering 
regimes to offer greater political openness and participatory democracy. The mock presidential elections in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname country-region}}Egypt{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} in 2005 are a case in point.

\par War also traumatized tourism, another major regional foreign exchange earner. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname country-region}}Egypt{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} alone collects $4 billion a y
ear from eager pyramid-gazers - about one ninth of its GDP. Add to that the effects of armed conflict on traffic in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}Suez Canal{\*\xmlclose}
, on investments and on expat remittances - and the country could well become the war's greatest victim.
\par In a recent economic conference of the Arab League, then Egyptian Minister of State for Foreign Affairs, Faiza Abu el-Naga, pegged the immediate losses to her country at $6-8 billion. More than 200,000 jobs were lost in tourism alone. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1
{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname country-region}}Egypt{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}'s Information and Decision Support C
entre (IDSC) distributed a study predicting $900 million in damages to the Jordanian economy and billions more to be incurred by oil-rich {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname country-region}}Saudi Arabia{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}.
\par The Arab Bank Federation foresees banking losses of up to $60 billion due to contraction in economic act
ivity both during the war and in its aftermath. This may be too pessimistic. But even the optimists talk about $30 billion in foregone revenues. The reconstruction of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname country-region}}
Iraq{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} could revitalize the sector - but American and European banks will probably monopolize the lucrative opportunity.
\par The war, and more so its protracted aftermath, are likely to have a stultifying effect on the investment climate.
\par {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname country-region}}Saudi Arabia{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns1{\factoidname country-region}}Egypt{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
